thread.title: Oconee County, Athens Academy advance to volleyball semifinals

author: Staff Reports
title: Oconee County, Athens Academy advance to volleyball semifinals
text:
Oconee County, Athens Academy advance to volleyball semifinals By Staff Reports sports@onlineathens.com – updated Sunday, October 25, 2015 - 10:11pm 
WATKINSVILLE | The volleyball teams from Oconee County and Jefferson met for the fourth time Saturday, and the Warriors came out on top again in a marathon battle, defeating the Dragons 25-21, 24-26, 25-21, 19-25, 15-12 to qualify for the final four of the Class AAA state tournament. 
Oconee County, which last defeated Jefferson on Oct. 10 for the Region 8-AAA title, was led by Ansley McClain (42 assists), Erin Brown (13 kills), Maggie Carlson (nine kills) and Emily Boswell (36 digs). 
Jefferson was led by Abby Wood (28 digs, three aces), Bre Arbanas (seven kills), Darien Matlock (eight digs), Lindsey Nilsen (16 kills), Grace Haney (21 assists), Madison Corbett (34 assists, 14 digs) and Olivia Przybysz (28 digs). 
The Warriors (31-12) will play at 6 p.m. Wednesday at Blessed Trinity in the semifinals. Jefferson ends its season with a school-record mark of 36-8. 
ATHENS ACADEMY ADVANCES 
At Roswell, Athens Academy dropped its first two matches to Fellowship Christian 20-25, 17-25, but the Spartans rallied to win the next three and advance to the semifinals of the Class A state tournament. 
Athens Academy won the final three games 25-18, 25-16, 25-11 to win the third-round match. 
The Spartans (37-2) will play at Calvary Day in Savannah on Wednesday. 
NORTH OCONEE KNOCKED OUT OF PLAYOFFS 
At Bogart, visiting Woodward Academy advanced to the semifinals of the Class AAAA state tournament with a 25-23, 25-23, 25-18 victory over North Oconee in the third round. 
The Titans finish the season at 36-9. Woodward Academy (30-17) will play Wednesday at Buford. 
TOP SEED WESTMINSTER CHRISTIAN ELIMINATED 
At Oxford, top-seeded Westminster Christian defeated North Georgia 3-1 (25-16, 23-25, 25-16, 25-21) in the quarterfinals of the GICAA state tournament but then fell to the Habersham School 3-0 (5-25, 7-25, 13-25) in the semifinals. 
In the North Georgia match, Eliza O’Rear had a seven-point service run to finish the first game and another seven-point run in the third game. Morgan Britt had six kills in the fourth game and the Lions recorded 40 digs. 
CROSS COUNTRY 
BLOCK WINS AT LAST CHANCE 
At the Carrollton Last Chance meet, Athens Academy’s Anna Marian Block finished first among 75 runners in the girls Class A-AA division in a time of 18 minutes, 28.62 seconds as the Spartans finished in third place with 80 points. Landmark Christian finished first with 30 points. 
In the girls AAA-AAAA race, East Jackson’s Sue Ann Morales finished second among 161 runners in a time of 20:14.81. In the Class race, Analee Bradech and Molly Silva of Apalachee finished ninth and 10th, respectively. Bradech crossed the line at 22:51.25 and Silva finished in 23:32.39. 
Apalachee finished fourth among seven teams with 101 points. Jones County won with 40 points. 
For the boys, Apalachee’s Merit Fontinel was the top finisher, coming in second among 79 runners in the Boys Class race in a time of 18:03.42. Teammate Nathan Crocker came in 10th in 18:46.10 and Apalachee finished second among eight teams with 80 points; Bleckly County won the division with 52 points. 
In the boys Class AAA-AAAA race, East Jackson’s Chandler Kennedy came in ninth among 211 runners in a time of 17:38.60 and his brother Chase Kennedy finished 10th in a time of 17:38.84. East Jackson finished ninth among 24 teams with 243 points; Westminster won the division with 90 points. 
In the boys Class A-AA race, Alex Branch of Athens Academy finished fifth among 103 runners in a time of 18:07.75, and teammate Ryan Iyer came in seventh at 18:20.92. Athens Academy finished second among 12 teams, with Landmark Christian coming in first with 26 points.
